  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear as though it came from legitimate sources. The process typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting a series of transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Making the laundered money appear legitimate by investing it into the economy or using it for legitimate purposes.\n\nMoney laundering is prohibited because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, terrorism financing, and more. Laws and regulations are in place globally to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities. Financial institutions and other entities are often required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures and report suspicious transactions to authorities.",
